$\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (5)(-1) - (-1)(5) \\ (-1)(4) - (4)(-1) \\ (4)(5) - (5)(4) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$



\begin{equation*}
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}}
\end{equation*} 

Notice that the resulting vector is the zero vector. This happens when the two original vectors are parallel to each other.

